{"title_page": "Keith Robertson (New Zealand rugby union)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography \n| name = Keith Robertson\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| nickname = \n| birth_name = Keith Robertson\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = New Zealand\n| death_place = \n| death_date = \n| ru_position =\n| height = \n| weight = \n| allblackid = \n| allblackno = \n| ru_nationalteam = \n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints =  \n| ru_province = \n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints = \n| ru_coachclubs = [[Rugby Southland]]<br/>[[Highlanders (rugby union)|Highlanders]] ''(Asst.)''<br/>[[Glasgow Warriors|Glasgow]]<br/>[[Scotland national under-21 rugby union team|Scotland Under 21]] ''(Asst.)''<br/>[[Clyde Earnscleugh]]\n| ru_coachyears =  <br/>1996\u20131997<br/>1997\u20131999<br/>1999\n| occupation = \n| family = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n}}\n\n'''Keith Robertson''' (born in New Zealand) is a former head coach of Glasgow Rugby, now known as the [[Glasgow Warriors]]. He took over the club from fellow New Zealander [[Kevin Greene (rugby union)|Kevin Greene]] in November 1997 when it was felt that the head coach position should be a full-time post.<ref name=\"post\" />\n\nPreviously a coach of Rugby Southland<ref name=\"southland\" /> and an assistant coach of [[Highlanders (rugby union)|Otago Highlanders]], Robertson applied for the Glasgow job when the Highlanders were on a tour of the UK. He was already earmarked as a potential candidate head coach by [[Jim Telfer]] in May 1997.<ref name=\"earmark\" />\n\nThis was a difficult period for the fledgling professional rugby game in Scotland. During Robertson's tenure at the club the 4 districts of Scotland were merged into two. The Glasgow club merged with the [[Caledonia Reds]] to become known as the Glasgow Caledonians. Meanwhile, Edinburgh Rugby merged with the [[Border Reivers (rugby union)|Border Reivers]] to become the Edinburgh Reivers.\n\nRobertson's philosophy was to learn with the players and belief was key. He stated \"When I come over I am not going to be saying to the boys that this or that is the way we do things in New Zealand, I fully expect that I will learn from Glasgow's players and they will tell me what they do. I enjoy motivating players to see what they can do more than dictating to them.\"\n\nHe also tried to put losses and rugby in perspective: \"A loss in sport is a loss, you pick yourself up, examine why you lost, and then go forward.... Don't talk to me about sporting pressure. The bloke with no money in Drumchapel has more pressure than any rugby player.\"<ref name=\"drumchapel\" />\n\nRobertson thought the Glasgow team in 1998 could have competed in the Super12 and won the European Cup.<ref name=\"super12\"/> In the Heineken Cup of 1998\u201399 Glasgow recorded only 2 wins out of the 6 group games; the others of the group consisting of [[Pontypridd RFC|Pontypridd]], [[Benetton Rugby|Benetton Treviso]] and [[US Colomiers|Colomiers]].<ref name=\"europe\" />\n\nIt was thought that Robertson struggled to cope with merging the [[Glasgow Warriors|Glasgow]] and [[Caledonia Reds]] players into one team.<ref name=\"struggle\"/>\n\nHe was replaced by [[Richie Dixon]] in January 1999. Robertson moved to helping the Scotland Under 21 side with [[Roy Laidlaw]] but left at the end of the season.\n\nRobertson is now the coach of [[Clyde-Earnscleugh]]<ref name=\"clyde\" /> in New Zealand.\n\n==References==\n<references>\n<ref name=\"post\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/kiwi-coach-lays-it-on-the-line-1.374483 |title=Kiwi coach lays it on the line (From Herald Scotland) |publisher=Heraldscotland.com |date= |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"southland\">{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/rugby-union-little-consolation-in-dour-victory-confidence-leaves-the-lions-in-their-final-game-before-saturdays-first-test-1490606.html |title=Rugby Union: Little consolation in dour victory: Confidence leaves the Lions in their final game before Saturday's first Test \u2013 Sport |publisher=The Independent |date=9 June 1993 |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"earmark\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/why-super-12-have-got-it-taped-1.397799 |title=Why Super 12 have got it taped (From Herald Scotland) |publisher=Heraldscotland.com |date= |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"drumchapel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/robertson-is-up-for-the-cup-1.333994 |title=Robertson is up for the cup (From Herald Scotland) |publisher=Heraldscotland.com |date= |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"super12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/HAIL+CALEDONIA%3B+Wainwright+backs+rookies+to+capture+European+glory.-a060562535 |title=HAIL CALEDONIA; Wainwright backs rookies to capture European glory. \u2013 Free Online Library |publisher=Thefreelibrary.com |date= |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"europe\">{{cite web|url=http://tournamentguides.epcrugby.com/eng/championscup/18739.php |title=Glasgow Warriors : Digital Tournament Guide &#124; Champions Cup |publisher=Tournamentguides.epcrugby.com |date=20 November 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"struggle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/kiwi-coach-for-glasgow-antipodean-triumvirate-set-to-run-the-show-at-hughenden-1.146121 |title=Kiwi coach for Glasgow Antipodean triumvirate set to run the show at Hughenden (From Herald Scotland) |publisher=Heraldscotland.com |date= |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"clyde\">{{cite web|last=Carroll |first=Joanne |url=http://www.odt.co.nz/sport/rugby/101103/rugby-close-competition-central?page=0%2C1 |title=Rugby: Close competition in Central (page 2) &#124; Otago Daily Times Online News : Otago, South Island, New Zealand & International News |publisher=Odt.co.nz |date=10 April 2010 |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n</references>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/robertson-is-up-for-the-cup-1.333994  Profile of Keith Robertson]\n\n{{Glasgow Warriors head coaches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robertson, Keith}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Glasgow Warriors coaches]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography \n| name = Keith Robertson\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| nickname = \n| birth_name = Keith Robertson\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = New Zealand\n| death_place = \n| death_date = \n| ru_position =\n| height = \n| weight = \n| allblackid = \n| allblackno = \n| ru_nationalteam = \n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints =  \n| ru_province = \n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints = \n| ru_coachclubs = [[Rugby Southland]]<br/>[[Highlanders (rugby union)|Highlanders]] ''(Asst.)''<br/>[[Glasgow Warriors|Glasgow]]<br/>[[Scotland national under-21 rugby union team|Scotland Under 21]] ''(Asst.)''<br/>[[Clyde Earnscleugh]]\n| ru_coachyears =  <br/>1996\u20131997<br/>1997\u20131999<br/>1999\n| occupation = \n| family = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n}}\n\n'''Keith Robertson''' (born in New Zealand) is a former head coach of Glasgow Rugby, now known as the [[Glasgow Warriors]]. He took over the club from fellow New Zealander [[Kevin Greene (rugby union)|Kevin Greene]] in November 1997 when it was felt that the head coach position should be a full-time post.<ref name=\"post\" />\n\nPreviously a coach of Rugby Southland<ref name=\"southland\" /> and an assistant coach of [[Highlanders (rugby union)|Otago Highlanders]], Robertson applied for the Glasgow job when the Highlanders were on a tour of the UK. He was already earmark