{"title_page": "James King (Scottish rugby union player)", "text_new": "{{moresources|date=September 2019}}\n{{other people||James King (disambiguation){{!}}James King}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name =  James King\n| image = \n| birth_name = James King\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|3|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], [[England]]\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| weight = 86kg\n| ru_position = [[Inside Centre|Centre]]\n| ru_currentclub = [[Edinburgh Rugby]]\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Melrose RFC]]\n| ru_amateuryears = 2008\u201310\n| ru_nationalteam = [[Scotland under 21 rugby union team|Scotland U21]]<br/>[[Scotland under 19 rugby union team|Scotland U19]]<br/>[[Scotland under 18 rugby union team|Scotland U18]]\n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints =\n| ru_clubyears = 2004 2007<br/>2007\u201308<br/>2010\u201313\n| ru_proclubs = [[Border Reivers (rugby union)|Border Reivers]]<br/>[[L'Aquila Rugby|L'Aquila]]<br/>[[Edinburgh Rugby|Edinburgh]]\n| ru_clubcaps = 4<br/><br/>30\n| ru_clubpoints = (15)<br/><br/>(5)\n| ru_clubupdate = 3 June 2013\n| youthyears = \n| youthclubs = \n| school = [[Berwick Academy, Berwick-upon-Tweed|Berwick High School]]\n}}\n\n'''James King''' (born 31 March 1986) is a Scottish rugby union player who plays for [[Edinburgh Rugby]] in the [[Pro14]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburghrugby.org/team/centres/james-king |title=James King |publisher=[[Edinburgh Rugby]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830105242/http://www.edinburghrugby.org/team/centres/james-king |archivedate=2012-08-30}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nHe has also represented Scotland at under-18, under-19 and under-21 level and was educated at Berwick High School. He has had spells with both [[Border Reivers (rugby union)|Border Reivers]] and [[L'Aquila Rugby|L'Aquila]], the outfit from central [[Italy]].\n\nKing scored his first try for the club away to [[Connacht Rugby|Connacht]] in April 2011, and followed this up by signing a two-year contract extension four days later.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, James}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Edinburgh Rugby players]]\n[[Category:Border Reivers players]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at North Berwick High School]]\n", "text_old": "{{moresources|date=September 2019}}\n{{other people||James King (disambiguation){{!}}James King}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name =  James King\n| image = \n| birth_name = James King\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|3|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], [[England]]\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| weight = 86kg\n| ru_position = [[Inside Centre|Centre]]\n| ru_currentclub = [[Edinburgh Rugby]]\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Melrose RFC]]\n| ru_amateuryears = 2008\u201310\n| ru_nationalteam = [[Scotland under 21 rugby union team|Scotland U21]]<br/>[[Scotland under 19 rugby union team|Scotland U19]]<br/>[[Scotland under 18 rugby union team|Scotland U18]]\n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints =\n| ru_clubyears = 2004 2007<br/>2007\u201308<br/>2010\u201313\n| ru_proclubs = [[Border Reivers]]<br/>[[L'Aquila Rugby|L'Aquila]]<br/>[[Edinburgh Rugby|Edinburgh]]\n| ru_clubcaps = 4<br/><br/>30\n| ru_clubpoints = (15)<br/><br/>(5)\n| ru_clubupdate = 3 June 2013\n| youthyears = \n| youthclubs = \n| school = [[Berwick Academy, Berwick-upon-Tweed|Berwick High School]]\n}}\n\n'''James King''' (born 31 March 1986) is a Scottish rugby union player who plays for [[Edinburgh Rugby]] in the [[Pro14]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburghrugby.org/team/centres/james-king |title=James King |publisher=[[Edinburgh Rugby]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830105242/http://www.edinburghrugby.org/team/centres/james-king |archivedate=2012-08-30}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nHe has also represented Scotland at under-18, under-19 and under-21 level and was educated at Berwick High School. He has had spells with both [[Border Reivers]] and [[L'Aquila Rugby|L'Aquila]], the outfit from central [[Italy]].\n\nKing scored his first try for the club away to [[Connacht Rugby|Connacht]] in April 2011, and followed this up by signing a two-year contract extension four days later.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, James}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Edinburgh Rugby players]]\n[[Category:Border Reivers players]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at North Berwick High School]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix sporting links (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_King_(Scottish_rugby_union_player)"}
{"title_page": "Mascarenhas (footballer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Angolan footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mascarenhas\n| image =  \n| fullname = Domingos Ant\u00f3nio da Silva\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1937|4|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[N'dalatando|Vila Salazar]], [[Portuguese Angola|Angola]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2015|8|25|1937|4|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]]\n| height =\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]  \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 =  \n| years1 = 1958\u20131959 | clubs1 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] | caps1 = 2 | goals1 = 1 \n| years2 = 1959\u20131962 | clubs2 = [[F.C. Barreirense|Barreirense]] | caps2 = 25 | goals2 = 10\n| years3 = 1962\u20131965 | clubs3 = [[Sporting CP]] | caps3 = 26 | goals3 = 12\n| years4 = 1965\u20131966 | clubs4 = [[F.C. Barreirense|Barreirense]] | caps4 = 17 | goals4 = 7 \n| years5 = 1966\u20131967 | clubs5 = [[G.D. Fabril|CUF]] | caps5 = 8 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 1967\u20131968 | clubs6 = Peniche | caps6 = | goals6 = \n| years7 = 1969\u20131971 | clubs7 = [[G.D. Riopele|Riopele]] | caps7 = | goals7 =\n| years8 = 1972\u20131975 | clubs8 = [[F.C. Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira|Pa\u00e7os Ferreira]] | caps8 = | goals8 =\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 =  \n| manageryears1 = | managerclubs1 = \n}}\n'''Domingos Ant\u00f3nio da Silva''' (28 April 1937 \u2013 25 August 2015), known as '''Mascarenhas''', was an [[Angola]]n [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\n==Club career==\nMascarenhas was born in [[N'dalatando|Vila Salazar]], [[Portuguese Angola]]. After [[1958\u201359 Primeira Liga|one season]] with [[S.L. Benfica]] and three with [[F.C. Barreirense]], he joined [[Sporting CP]] in 1962; during his three-year spell with the [[Lisbon]] club, he scored 80 goals in 107 matches all appearances comprised, even [[Exhibition game|friendlies]].\n\nIn the 1963 [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|Portuguese Cup]] final, Mascarenhas scored once in a 4\u20130 victory over [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]]. The following campaign, in Sporting's [[1963\u201364 European Cup Winners' Cup|victorious campaign]] in the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]], he netted six times in a 16\u20131 home rout of [[APOEL FC]] ([[UEFA|European competition]] record), adding another in [[1964 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|the final]] against [[MTK Budapest FC]], the 3\u20133 leading to a replay in [[Antwerp]] which ended with a 1\u20130 win for the ''Lions''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ecwc/news/kind=8192/newsid=3569.html|title=1963/64: Sporting at the second attempt|publisher=UEFA|date=17 August 2001|accessdate=9 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080519112850/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ecwc/news/kind%3D8192/newsid%3D3569.html|archivedate=19 May 2008}}</ref><ref>\n[http://www.sporting.pt/Clube/Historia/Biografias/biografia_mascarenhas.asp Biografia (Biography)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812060554/http://www.sporting.pt/Clube/Historia/Biografias/biografia_mascarenhas.asp|date=12 August 2010}}; at Sporting CP (in Portuguese)</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMascarenhas died on 25 August 2015 at the S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 Hospital in [[Lisbon]], after a long illness. He was 78 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=567457|title=Morreu Mascarenhas|trans-title=Mascarenhas has died|newspaper=[[A Bola]]|language=Portuguese|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=25 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826183736/http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=567457|archivedate=26 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n\n{{Ta\u00e7a de Portugal top scorers}}\n{{UEFA Cup Winners' Cup top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mascarenhas}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Angolan footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:LigaPro players]]\n[[Category:S.L. Benfica footballers]]\n[[Category:F.C. Barreirense players]]\n[[Category:Sporting CP footballers]]\n[[Category:G.D. Fabril players]]\n[[Category:G.D. Peniche players]]\n[[Category:G.D. Riopele players]]\n[[Category:F.C. Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira players]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mascarenhas\n| image =  \n| fullname = Domingos Ant\u00f3nio da Silva\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1937|4|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[N'dalatando|Vila Salazar]], [[Portuguese Angola|Angola]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2015|8|25|1937|4|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]]\n| height =\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]  \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 =  \n| years1 = 1958\u20131959 | clubs1 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] | caps1 = 2 | goals1 = 1 \n| years2 = 1959\u20131962 | clubs2 = [[F.C. Barreirense|Barreirense]] | caps2 = 25 | goals2 = 10\n| years3 = 1962\u20131965 | clubs3 = [[Sporting CP]] | caps3 = 26 | goals3 = 12\n| years4 = 1965\u20131966 | clubs4 = [[F.C. Barreirense|Barreirense]] | caps4 = 17 | goals4 = 7 \n| years5 = 1966\u20131967 | clubs5 = [[G.D. Fabril|CUF]] | caps5 = 8 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 1967\u20131968 | clubs6 = Peniche | caps6 = | goals6 = \n| years7 = 1969\u20131971 | clubs7 = [[G.D. Riopele|Riopele]] | caps7 = | goals7 =\n| years8 = 1972\u20131975 | clubs8 = [[F.C. Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira|Pa\u00e7os Ferreira]] | caps8 = | goals8 =\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 =  \n| manageryears1 = | managerclubs1 = \n}}\n'''Domingos Ant\u00f3nio da Silva''' (28 April 1937 \u2013 25 August 2015), known as '''Mascarenhas''', was an [[Angola]]n [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\n==Club career==\nMascarenhas was born in [[N'dalatando|Vila Salazar]], [[Portuguese Angola]]. After [[1958\u201359 Primeira Liga|one season]] with [[S.L. Benfica]] and three with [[F.C. Barreirense]], he joined [[Sporting CP]] in 1962; during his three-year spell with the [[Lisbon]] club, he scored 80 goals in 107 matches all appearances comprised, even [[Exhibition game|friendlies]].\n\nIn the 1963 [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|Portuguese Cup]] final, Mascarenhas scored once in a 4\u20130 victory over [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]]. The following campaign, in Sporting's [[1963\u201364 European Cup Winners' Cup|victorious campaign]] in the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]], he netted six times in a 16\u20131 home rout of [[APOEL FC]] ([[UEFA|European competition]] record), adding another in [[1964 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|the final]] against [[MTK Budapest FC]], the 3\u20133 leading to a replay in [[Antwerp]] which ended with a 1\u20130 win for the ''Lions''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ecwc/news/kind=8192/newsid=3569.html|title=1963/64: Sporting at the second attempt|publisher=UEFA|date=17 August 2001|accessdate=9 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080519112850/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ecwc/news/kind%3D8192/newsid%3D3569.html|archivedate=19 May 2008}}</ref><ref>\n[http://www.sporting.pt/Clube/Historia/Biografias/biografia_mascarenhas.asp Biografia (Biography)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812060554/http://www.sporting.pt/Clube/Historia/Biografias/biografia_mascarenhas.asp|date=12 August 2010}}; at Sporting CP (in Portuguese)</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMascarenhas died on 25 August 2015 at the S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 Hospital in [[Lisbon]], after a long illness. He was 78 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=567457|title=Morreu Mascarenhas|trans-title=Mascarenhas has died|newspaper=[[A Bola]]|language=Portuguese|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=25 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826183736/http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=567457|archivedate=26 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n\n{{Ta\u00e7a de Portugal top scorers}}\n{{UEFA Cup Winners' Cup top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mascarenhas}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Angolan footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:LigaPro players]]\n[[Category:S.L. Benfica footballers]]\n[[Category:F.C. Barreirense players]]\n[[Category:Sporting CP footballers]]\n[[Category:G.D. Fabril players]]\n[[Category:G.D. Peniche players]]\n[[Category:G.D. Riopele players]]\n[[Category:F.C. Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira players]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Angolan footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Angolan footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mascarenhas_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Scottish Rugby Union", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{National rugby union\n| unionname      = Scottish Rugby Union\n| nativename     = Aonadh Rugbaidh na h-Alba\n| logo           = Scottish rugby logo.svg\n| logosize       = 150px\n| founded        = {{Start date and age|1873}}\n| IRB            = 1886 (founder)\n| region         = [[FIRA - Association of European Rugby|FIRA-AER]]\n| regionyear     = 1999\n| headquarters = [[Murrayfield Stadium]]<br>[[Edinburgh]]<br>EH12 5PJ\n| coords = {{coord|55|56|32.07|N|3|14|27.38|W|type:landmark|display=it}}\n| president      = [[Dee Bradbury]]\n| coach          =  [[Gregor Townsend]] \n| womenscoach    = [[Shade Munro]]\n| sevenscoach    = [[John Dalziel]]\n| countryflag    = Scotland\n| url            = {{url|www.scottishrugby.org}}\n|womensevenscoach=Scott Wight}}\n\nThe '''Scottish Rugby Union''' ('''SRU'''; {{lang-gd|Aonadh Rugbaidh na h-Alba}}) is the [[Sport governing body|governing body]] of [[rugby union in Scotland]]. It is the second oldest Rugby Union, having been founded in 1873, as the '''Scottish Football Union'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rfu.com/twickenhamstadium/worldrugbymuseum/rugbyhistory/historyofthegame |title=History of the game |publisher=[[Rugby Football Union]] |accessdate=11 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110202501/http://www.rfu.com/twickenhamstadium/worldrugbymuseum/rugbyhistory/historyofthegame |archive-date=10 January 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The SRU oversees the national league system, known as the [[Scottish League Championship]], and the Scottish National teams. The SRU is headed by the President (Dee Bradbury) and Chairman (Colin Grassie), with Mark Dodson acting as the Chief Executive Officer. Bradbury became the first female president of a Tier 1 rugby nation upon her appointment on 4 August 2018.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of rugby union in Scotland}}\n\n===1873 \u2014 1920s===\nThe Scottish Football Union was founded on Monday 3 March 1873 at a meeting held at [[Glasgow Academy]], Elmbank Street, Glasgow. Eight clubs were represented at the foundation, [[Glasgow Academicals RFC|Glasgow Academicals]]; [[Edinburgh Academical Football Club]]; [[West of Scotland F.C.]]; [[University of St Andrews Rugby Football Club]]; [[Royal High School (Edinburgh)#Sports and games|Royal High School FP]]; [[Merchistonian FC|Merchistonians]]; [[Edinburgh University RFC]]; and [[Glasgow University Rugby Football Club|Glasgow University]]. Five of these clubs were, at the time of founding the Scottish Football Union, already members of the previously instituted [[Rugby Football Union]]. Although the RFU now represents exclusively English clubs, in its first few years it had members from outside England, there being no other national union. West of Scotland, Glasgow Academicals and [[Edinburgh University RFC|Edinburgh University]] had joined the RFU in 1871 and Edinburgh Academicals and Royal High School FP had joined in 1872. These five renounced membership of the RFU to join the SFU.\n\nThe SFU was a founding member of the International Rugby Football Board, now known as [[World Rugby]], in 1886 with [[Irish Rugby Football Union|Ireland]] and [[Welsh Rugby Union|Wales]]. (England refused to join until 1890.)\n\nIn 1924 the SFU changed its name to become the Scottish Rugby Union.<ref name=\"1925GS\">{{cite web| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0020/print.shtml |title=First Scottish Grand Slam |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-10-27 |last=MacDonald |first=Paul}}</ref> International games were played at [[Inverleith]] from 1899 to 1925 when Murrayfield was opened.\n\n===1990s \u2014 present===\nThe SRU owns [[Murrayfield Stadium]] which is the main home ground of the [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scottish national team]], though in 2004 international rugby games were played at [[Hampden Park]] in [[Glasgow]] and [[McDiarmid Park]] in [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]], as part of the SRU's campaign to reach out to new audiences outside the traditional rugby areas.\n\nWhen the [[Heineken Cup]] (now replaced by the [[European Rugby Champions Cup]]) was suggested SRU officials were concerned that Scottish club sides could not compete against the best teams from France and England and that centrally funded so-called 'super-district' teams might do better.\n\nThe four traditional districts\u2014the South (renamed [[Border Reivers (rugby union)|Border Reivers]]), Edinburgh, Glasgow and the North & Midlands (rebranded as [[Caledonia Reds]])\u2014were given the go-ahead to take part in Europe. For the first two seasons, players were still released to play for their clubs in domestic competition, but eventually the districts became full-time operations.\n\nThen financial difficulties \u2013 the SRU's high debt, partly as a result of the redevelopment of [[Murrayfield Stadium|Murrayfield]] \u2013 called for retrenchment. After two seasons, financial difficulties forced the SRU to merge the four teams into two. Edinburgh merged with the Border Reivers to form a team to be known as Edinburgh Reivers. Glasgow merged with Caledonian to form a team to be known as Glasgow Caledonian.\n\n[[Border Reivers (rugby)|The Borders]] was resurrected in 2002 and joined the second season of the [[Pro14|Celtic League]]. As a consequence Edinburgh Reivers became simply [[Edinburgh Rugby]] and Glasgow became Glasgow Rugby.<ref name=AnnRep2003>{{cite web| url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/pdfs/SRU_AnnualReport.pdf |title=SRU Annual Report 2003-04|publisher=Scottish Rugby Union |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050120183950/http://www.scottishrugby.org/pdfs/SRU_AnnualReport.pdf |archivedate=20 January 2005}}</ref> In 2005, all three teams adopted new names. The Borders readopted the name Border Reivers; Edinburgh became Edinburgh Gunners, but would revert to Edinburgh in 2006; and Glasgow became [[Glasgow Warriors]]. Furthermore, the SRU planned to have a world class rugby side for each city or large town in Scotland, when financial circumstances permitted.<ref name=dictators>{{cite news| url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/rugby.cfm?id=51502005 |title= SRU accused of becoming dictatorship |publisher=[[The Scotsman]] |date=15 January 2005 |accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, The Borders team was disbanded yet again as a result of continuing financial difficulties. In the same year, the SRU began organising the [[Scotland Sevens]], first held in Edinburgh and later in Glasgow. For several years, it was the final event in the annual [[IRB Sevens World Series|Sevens World Series]], but that distinction now belongs to [[London Sevens|London]].\n\nOn 21 November 2009 Scotland beat Australia 9\u20138 after 17 attempts in 27 years.\n\nIn the Season 2010\u201311 the SRU had a contractual dispute with the Season Ticket Holders of Edinburgh Rugby.\n\nOn 22 December 2010 at Edinburgh Sheriff Court (Small Claims) the Sheriff ruled the Scottish Rugby Union had entered a contract between itself and Season Ticket Holders of Edinburgh Rugby Club. The Sheriff also found that the SRU had breached the contract between itself and Edinburgh Rugby Club (a Division of the SRU). Although it was found that the SRU had breached the contract, the Sheriff could not make an order instructing the SRU to comply with its obligation under that contract.\n\n===Centenary celebrations===\nThe SRU celebrated its centenary in 1973 with a number of events. Among these was the [[1973 International Seven-A-Side Tournament]], the first sevens tournament to have national representative sides. The programme for that event also sported the new coat of arms of the SRU that was granted by the [[Lord Lyon King of Arms]] on 28 February 1973, for the centenary season. The coat of arms is still in use today, but in the main the SRU use the commercial thistle logo on jerseys and stationary. The coat of arms has the motto ''\"Non Sine Gloria\"'', meaning ''\"Not Without Glory\"''.\n\n==Domestic Rugby==\n{{see also|Scottish rugby union system|Rugby union in Scotland}}\n\nThe SRU oversees the national league system, known as the [[Scottish League Championship]], and consisting of:\n* a [[Scottish Premiership (rugby)|Premiership]] of 20 teams across 2 divisions.\n* a [[Scottish Championship Leagues|National Leagues]] of 20 teams across 2 regional divisions.\n* [[Scottish Regional Leagues|Regional Leagues]] of 150 clubs in 18 divisions across three regions\n\nIt also oversees the [[Scottish Cup (rugby union)|Scottish Cup]]. It is not directly responsible for local, university or 2nd XV leagues.\n\n===Women's & Girls Rugby===\n\nSee also [[Scottish Women's Rugby]].\n\nSince the [[Scottish Women's Rugby Union]] merged with Scottish Rugby in 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/women-vote-to-join-up-with-the-sru-1-1042058|title=Women vote to join up with the SRU|publisher=}}</ref> the governing body also oversees Women's Fixtures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-results|title=Fixtures & Results - Scottish Rugby Union|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=2 Tennent's Women's Premier League 2018\u201319] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=2|title=Fixtures & Results - Scottish Rugby Union|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=6 Tennent's Women's National League 1 2018\u201319]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=6|title=Fixtures & Results - Tennent's Women's National League 1|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=7 Tennent's Women's National League 2 2018\u201319]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=7|title=Fixtures & Results - Tennent's Women's National League 2|last=|first=|date=|website=Scottish Rugby|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=42 Tennent's Women's North League 2018-19]\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=204 Women's National Development League 2018-19]\n\nA National Cup competition:\n\n*Sarah Beaney Cup 2015\u201316<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-results/?competition=108896|title=Fixtures & Results - Scottish Rugby Union|publisher=}}</ref>\n*BT Women's Bowl<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-results/?competition=112864|title=Fixtures & Results - Scottish Rugby Union|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRegional Cup Competition:\n\n*Donna Kennedy Cup<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/news/15/10/08/inaugural-women%E2%80%99s-cup-set-centre-stage-bt-murrayfield|title=Inaugural women\u2019s Cup set for centre stage at BT Murrayfield - Scottish Rugby Union|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==National teams==\n{{main article|Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland national rugby sevens team}}\nThe SRU oversees Scotland's national teams. The most prominent team is the [[Scotland national rugby union team]], which competes in the Six Nations tournament every year and in the Rugby World Cup every four years. The SRU also oversees the [[Scotland national rugby sevens team|Scotland national sevens team]], which competes every year in the [[World Rugby Sevens Series]]. And the SRU oversees the Scotland national women\u2019s rugby team.\n\nThe head coach of the Scotland national rugby union team is [[Gregor Townsend]], who began in June 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/scotland/gregor-townsend-era-begins-but-pressures-remain-the-same-1-4471772 |title=Gregor Townsend era begins but pressures remain the same |first=Lewis |last=Stuart |work=The Scotsman |date=10 June 2017|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref> [[Scott Johnson (rugby coach)|Scott Johnson]] is Director of Rugby.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/scott-johnson-appointed-to-sru-director-role-1-2919359 |title=Scott Johnson appointed to SRU director role |first=David |last=Ferguson |work=The Scotsman |date=3 May 2013 |accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe head coach of the Scottish national women's rugby team is [[Shade Munro]].\n\n==North American initiatives==\nOn 28 March 2019, the SRU announced that it had taken a minority stake in [[Old Glory DC]], a team set to begin play in [[Major League Rugby]] (MLR), the current top level of the sport in the [[United States]] and [[Canada]], in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/rugby/story/_/id/26379639/scottish-rugby-take-minority-stake-new-us-team |title=Scottish Rugby take minority stake in new U.S. team |website=ESPN.com |date=28 March 2019 |accessdate=28 March 2019}}</ref> As MLR operates on a \"single-entity\" business model similar to the two countries' [[Major League Soccer]], with the league owning all teams and the team operators being league shareholders,<ref>{{cite news |date=17 November 2017 |title=Major League Rugby nears kick-off as next attempt to make US a union power |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/nov/17/major-league-rugby-conor-mcgregor |accessdate=19 November 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119130540/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/nov/17/major-league-rugby-conor-mcgregor |archivedate=19 November 2017}}</ref> this effectively meant that the SRU had taken a small stake in MLR itself.\n\n==Personnel==\n\n{{Main article|President of the Scottish Rugby Union}}\n{{Main article|List of Scottish Rugby Union Presidents}}\n\nThe current president is [[Dee Bradbury]]. In August 2016 the board elected Colin Grassie to the position of Chairman, taking up the post in January 2017 for a three year term.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/news/16/09/16/scottish-rugby-elects-new-chairman-2017 |title=Scottish Rugby elects new Chairman for 2017 |website=www.scottishrugby.org |date=16 August 2017 |accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>  The Chief Executive Officer is Mark Dodson.<ref name=\"Scotsman 10Aug2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby/latest/sru-chief-mark-dodson-lauds-big-step-forward-1-3853891 |title=SRU chief Mark Dodson lauds \u2018big step forward\u2019 |first=Duncan |last=Smith |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=10 August 2015 |accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, it was announced that [[Sheila Begbie]] had been appointed to the newly created post of Head of Women's Rugby, reporting directly to the Director of Rugby and she was due to commence this role in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/27619363 |title=Sheila Begbie leaves women's football for Scottish Rugby role |work=BBC News |date=29 May 2014|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Rugby union in Scotland]]\n* [[Murrayfield Stadium]]\n* [[Edinburgh Sevens|Edinburgh 7s]]<!--The \"7s\" reflects the official SRU branding of the event.-->\n* [[Scottish Women's Rugby]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.scottishrugby.org}}\n\n\n{{Scotland national rugby union team}}\u2009\n{{Rugby union in Scotland}}\n{{IRB Unions}}\n{{Scottish Sport}}\n\n[[Category:1873 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:19th century in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Rugby union in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Sports governing bodies in Scotland|Rugby union]]\n[[Category:Rugby union governing bodies in Scotland]]\n[[Category:World Rugby members]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Scottish Rugby Union| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{National rugby union\n| unionname      = Scottish Rugby Union\n| nativename     = Aonadh Rugbaidh na h-Alba\n| logo           = Scottish rugby logo.svg\n| logosize       = 150px\n| founded        = {{Start date and age|1873}}\n| IRB            = 1886 (founder)\n| region         = [[FIRA - Association of European Rugby|FIRA-AER]]\n| regionyear     = 1999\n| headquarters = [[Murrayfield Stadium]]<br>[[Edinburgh]]<br>EH12 5PJ\n| coords = {{coord|55|56|32.07|N|3|14|27.38|W|type:landmark|display=it}}\n| president      = [[Dee Bradbury]]\n| coach          =  [[Gregor Townsend]] \n| womenscoach    = [[Shade Munro]]\n| sevenscoach    = [[John Dalziel]]\n| countryflag    = Scotland\n| url            = {{url|www.scottishrugby.org}}\n|womensevenscoach=Scott Wight}}\n\nThe '''Scottish Rugby Union''' ('''SRU'''; {{lang-gd|Aonadh Rugbaidh na h-Alba}}) is the [[Sport governing body|governing body]] of [[rugby union in Scotland]]. It is the second oldest Rugby Union, having been founded in 1873, as the '''Scottish Football Union'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rfu.com/twickenhamstadium/worldrugbymuseum/rugbyhistory/historyofthegame |title=History of the game |publisher=[[Rugby Football Union]] |accessdate=11 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110202501/http://www.rfu.com/twickenhamstadium/worldrugbymuseum/rugbyhistory/historyofthegame |archive-date=10 January 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The SRU oversees the national league system, known as the [[Scottish League Championship]], and the Scottish National teams. The SRU is headed by the President (Dee Bradbury) and Chairman (Colin Grassie), with Mark Dodson acting as the Chief Executive Officer. Bradbury became the first female president of a Tier 1 rugby nation upon her appointment on 4 August 2018.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of rugby union in Scotland}}\n\n===1873 \u2014 1920s===\nThe Scottish Football Union was founded on Monday 3 March 1873 at a meeting held at [[Glasgow Academy]], Elmbank Street, Glasgow. Eight clubs were represented at the foundation, [[Glasgow Academicals RFC|Glasgow Academicals]]; [[Edinburgh Academical Football Club]]; [[West of Scotland F.C.]]; [[University of St Andrews Rugby Football Club]]; [[Royal High School (Edinburgh)#Sports and games|Royal High School FP]]; [[Merchistonian FC|Merchistonians]]; [[Edinburgh University RFC]]; and [[Glasgow University Rugby Football Club|Glasgow University]]. Five of these clubs were, at the time of founding the Scottish Football Union, already members of the previously instituted [[Rugby Football Union]]. Although the RFU now represents exclusively English clubs, in its first few years it had members from outside England, there being no other national union. West of Scotland, Glasgow Academicals and [[Edinburgh University RFC|Edinburgh University]] had joined the RFU in 1871 and Edinburgh Academicals and Royal High School FP had joined in 1872. These five renounced membership of the RFU to join the SFU.\n\nThe SFU was a founding member of the International Rugby Football Board, now known as [[World Rugby]], in 1886 with [[Irish Rugby Football Union|Ireland]] and [[Welsh Rugby Union|Wales]]. (England refused to join until 1890.)\n\nIn 1924 the SFU changed its name to become the Scottish Rugby Union.<ref name=\"1925GS\">{{cite web| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0020/print.shtml |title=First Scottish Grand Slam |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-10-27 |last=MacDonald |first=Paul}}</ref> International games were played at [[Inverleith]] from 1899 to 1925 when Murrayfield was opened.\n\n===1990s \u2014 present===\nThe SRU owns [[Murrayfield Stadium]] which is the main home ground of the [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scottish national team]], though in 2004 international rugby games were played at [[Hampden Park]] in [[Glasgow]] and [[McDiarmid Park]] in [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]], as part of the SRU's campaign to reach out to new audiences outside the traditional rugby areas.\n\nWhen the [[Heineken Cup]] (now replaced by the [[European Rugby Champions Cup]]) was suggested SRU officials were concerned that Scottish club sides could not compete against the best teams from France and England and that centrally funded so-called 'super-district' teams might do better.\n\nThe four traditional districts\u2014the South (renamed [[Border Reivers]]), Edinburgh, Glasgow and the North & Midlands (rebranded as [[Caledonia Reds]])\u2014were given the go-ahead to take part in Europe. For the first two seasons, players were still released to play for their clubs in domestic competition, but eventually the districts became full-time operations.\n\nThen financial difficulties \u2013 the SRU's high debt, partly as a result of the redevelopment of [[Murrayfield Stadium|Murrayfield]] \u2013 called for retrenchment. After two seasons, financial difficulties forced the SRU to merge the four teams into two. Edinburgh merged with the Border Reivers to form a team to be known as Edinburgh Reivers. Glasgow merged with Caledonian to form a team to be known as Glasgow Caledonian.\n\n[[Border Reivers (rugby)|The Borders]] was resurrected in 2002 and joined the second season of the [[Pro14|Celtic League]]. As a consequence Edinburgh Reivers became simply [[Edinburgh Rugby]] and Glasgow became Glasgow Rugby.<ref name=AnnRep2003>{{cite web| url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/pdfs/SRU_AnnualReport.pdf |title=SRU Annual Report 2003-04|publisher=Scottish Rugby Union |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050120183950/http://www.scottishrugby.org/pdfs/SRU_AnnualReport.pdf |archivedate=20 January 2005}}</ref> In 2005, all three teams adopted new names. The Borders readopted the name Border Reivers; Edinburgh became Edinburgh Gunners, but would revert to Edinburgh in 2006; and Glasgow became [[Glasgow Warriors]]. Furthermore, the SRU planned to have a world class rugby side for each city or large town in Scotland, when financial circumstances permitted.<ref name=dictators>{{cite news| url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/rugby.cfm?id=51502005 |title= SRU accused of becoming dictatorship |publisher=[[The Scotsman]] |date=15 January 2005 |accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, The Borders team was disbanded yet again as a result of continuing financial difficulties. In the same year, the SRU began organising the [[Scotland Sevens]], first held in Edinburgh and later in Glasgow. For several years, it was the final event in the annual [[IRB Sevens World Series|Sevens World Series]], but that distinction now belongs to [[London Sevens|London]].\n\nOn 21 November 2009 Scotland beat Australia 9\u20138 after 17 attempts in 27 years.\n\nIn the Season 2010\u201311 the SRU had a contractual dispute with the Season Ticket Holders of Edinburgh Rugby.\n\nOn 22 December 2010 at Edinburgh Sheriff Court (Small Claims) the Sheriff ruled the Scottish Rugby Union had entered a contract between itself and Season Ticket Holders of Edinburgh Rugby Club. The Sheriff also found that the SRU had breached the contract between itself and Edinburgh Rugby Club (a Division of the SRU). Although it was found that the SRU had breached the contract, the Sheriff could not make an order instructing the SRU to comply with its obligation under that contract.\n\n===Centenary celebrations===\nThe SRU celebrated its centenary in 1973 with a number of events. Among these was the [[1973 International Seven-A-Side Tournament]], the first sevens tournament to have national representative sides. The programme for that event also sported the new coat of arms of the SRU that was granted by the [[Lord Lyon King of Arms]] on 28 February 1973, for the centenary season. The coat of arms is still in use today, but in the main the SRU use the commercial thistle logo on jerseys and stationary. The coat of arms has the motto ''\"Non Sine Gloria\"'', meaning ''\"Not Without Glory\"''.\n\n==Domestic Rugby==\n{{see also|Scottish rugby union system|Rugby union in Scotland}}\n\nThe SRU oversees the national league system, known as the [[Scottish League Championship]], and consisting of:\n* a [[Scottish Premiership (rugby)|Premiership]] of 20 teams across 2 divisions.\n* a [[Scottish Championship Leagues|National Leagues]] of 20 teams across 2 regional divisions.\n* [[Scottish Regional Leagues|Regional Leagues]] of 150 clubs in 18 divisions across three regions\n\nIt also oversees the [[Scottish Cup (rugby union)|Scottish Cup]]. It is not directly responsible for local, university or 2nd XV leagues.\n\n===Women's & Girls Rugby===\n\nSee also [[Scottish Women's Rugby]].\n\nSince the [[Scottish Women's Rugby Union]] merged with Scottish Rugby in 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/women-vote-to-join-up-with-the-sru-1-1042058|title=Women vote to join up with the SRU|publisher=}}</ref> the governing body also oversees Women's Fixtures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-results|title=Fixtures & Results - Scottish Rugby Union|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=2 Tennent's Women's Premier League 2018\u201319] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=2|title=Fixtures & Results - Scottish Rugby Union|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=6 Tennent's Women's National League 1 2018\u201319]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=6|title=Fixtures & Results - Tennent's Women's National League 1|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=7 Tennent's Women's National League 2 2018\u201319]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=7|title=Fixtures & Results - Tennent's Women's National League 2|last=|first=|date=|website=Scottish Rugby|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=42 Tennent's Women's North League 2018-19]\n*[http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-and-results?competition=204 Women's National Development League 2018-19]\n\nA National Cup competition:\n\n*Sarah Beaney Cup 2015\u201316<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-results/?competition=108896|title=Fixtures & Results - Scottish Rugby Union|publisher=}}</ref>\n*BT Women's Bowl<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/fixtures-results/?competition=112864|title=Fixtures & Results - Scottish Rugby Union|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRegional Cup Competition:\n\n*Donna Kennedy Cup<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/news/15/10/08/inaugural-women%E2%80%99s-cup-set-centre-stage-bt-murrayfield|title=Inaugural women\u2019s Cup set for centre stage at BT Murrayfield - Scottish Rugby Union|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==National teams==\n{{main article|Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland national rugby sevens team}}\nThe SRU oversees Scotland's national teams. The most prominent team is the [[Scotland national rugby union team]], which competes in the Six Nations tournament every year and in the Rugby World Cup every four years. The SRU also oversees the [[Scotland national rugby sevens team|Scotland national sevens team]], which competes every year in the [[World Rugby Sevens Series]]. And the SRU oversees the Scotland national women\u2019s rugby team.\n\nThe head coach of the Scotland national rugby union team is [[Gregor Townsend]], who began in June 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/scotland/gregor-townsend-era-begins-but-pressures-remain-the-same-1-4471772 |title=Gregor Townsend era begins but pressures remain the same |first=Lewis |last=Stuart |work=The Scotsman |date=10 June 2017|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref> [[Scott Johnson (rugby coach)|Scott Johnson]] is Director of Rugby.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/scott-johnson-appointed-to-sru-director-role-1-2919359 |title=Scott Johnson appointed to SRU director role |first=David |last=Ferguson |work=The Scotsman |date=3 May 2013 |accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe head coach of the Scottish national women's rugby team is [[Shade Munro]].\n\n==North American initiatives==\nOn 28 March 2019, the SRU announced that it had taken a minority stake in [[Old Glory DC]], a team set to begin play in [[Major League Rugby]] (MLR), the current top level of the sport in the [[United States]] and [[Canada]], in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/rugby/story/_/id/26379639/scottish-rugby-take-minority-stake-new-us-team |title=Scottish Rugby take minority stake in new U.S. team |website=ESPN.com |date=28 March 2019 |accessdate=28 March 2019}}</ref> As MLR operates on a \"single-entity\" business model similar to the two countries' [[Major League Soccer]], with the league owning all teams and the team operators being league shareholders,<ref>{{cite news |date=17 November 2017 |title=Major League Rugby nears kick-off as next attempt to make US a union power |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/nov/17/major-league-rugby-conor-mcgregor |accessdate=19 November 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119130540/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/nov/17/major-league-rugby-conor-mcgregor |archivedate=19 November 2017}}</ref> this effectively meant that the SRU had taken a small stake in MLR itself.\n\n==Personnel==\n\n{{Main article|President of the Scottish Rugby Union}}\n{{Main article|List of Scottish Rugby Union Presidents}}\n\nThe current president is [[Dee Bradbury]]. In August 2016 the board elected Colin Grassie to the position of Chairman, taking up the post in January 2017 for a three year term.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.scottishrugby.org/news/16/09/16/scottish-rugby-elects-new-chairman-2017 |title=Scottish Rugby elects new Chairman for 2017 |website=www.scottishrugby.org |date=16 August 2017 |accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>  The Chief Executive Officer is Mark Dodson.<ref name=\"Scotsman 10Aug2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby/latest/sru-chief-mark-dodson-lauds-big-step-forward-1-3853891 |title=SRU chief Mark Dodson lauds \u2018big step forward\u2019 |first=Duncan |last=Smith |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=10 August 2015 |accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, it was announced that [[Sheila Begbie]] had been appointed to the newly created post of Head of Women's Rugby, reporting directly to the Director of Rugby and she was due to commence this role in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/27619363 |title=Sheila Begbie leaves women's football for Scottish Rugby role |work=BBC News |date=29 May 2014|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Rugby union in Scotland]]\n* [[Murrayfield Stadium]]\n* [[Edinburgh Sevens|Edinburgh 7s]]<!--The \"7s\" reflects the official SRU branding of the event.-->\n* [[Scottish Women's Rugby]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.scottishrugby.org}}\n\n\n{{Scotland national rugby union team}}\u2009\n{{Rugby union in Scotland}}\n{{IRB Unions}}\n{{Scottish Sport}}\n\n[[Category:1873 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:19th century in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Rugby union in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Sports governing bodies in Scotland|Rugby union]]\n[[Category:Rugby union governing bodies in Scotland]]\n[[Category:World Rugby members]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Scottish Rugby Union| ]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix sporting links (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scottish_Rugby_Union"}
